#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:2
msgid "printf - display text according to a format string"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:5
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr "概要"

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:7
msgid "printf FORMAT [ARGUMENT ...]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:12
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:16
msgid ""
"NOTE: This page documents the fish builtin ``printf``. To see the "
"documentation on any non-fish versions, use ``command man printf``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:19
msgid ""
"``printf`` uses the format string *FORMAT* to print the *ARGUMENT* "
"arguments. This means that it takes format specifiers in the format string "
"and replaces each with an argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:21
msgid ""
"The *FORMAT* argument is re-used as many times as necessary to convert all "
"of the given arguments. So ``printf %s\\n flounder catfish clownfish shark`` "
"will print four lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:23
msgid ""
"Unlike :doc:`echo <echo>`, ``printf`` does not append a new line unless it "
"is specified as part of the string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:25
msgid ""
"It doesn't support any options, so there is no need for a ``--`` separator, "
"which makes it easier to use for arbitrary input than ``echo``. [#]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:28
msgid "Format Specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:29
msgid ""
"Valid format specifiers are taken from the C library function ``printf(3)``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:31
msgid ""
"``%d`` or ``%i``: Argument will be used as decimal integer (signed or "
"unsigned)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:33
msgid "``%o``: An octal unsigned integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:35
msgid ""
"``%u``: An unsigned decimal integer - this means negative numbers will wrap "
"around"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:37
msgid "``%x`` or ``%X``: An unsigned hexadecimal integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:39
msgid ""
"``%f``, ``%g`` or ``%G``: A floating-point number. ``%f`` defaults to 6 "
"places after the decimal point (which is locale-dependent - e.g. in de_DE it "
"will be a ``,``). ``%g`` and ``%G`` will trim trailing zeroes and switch to "
"scientific notation (like ``%e``) if the numbers get small or large enough."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:41
msgid ""
"``%e`` or ``%E``: A floating-point number in scientific (XXXeYY) notation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:43
msgid "``%s``: A string"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:45
msgid ""
"``%b``: As a string, interpreting backslash escapes, except that octal "
"escapes are of the form \\0 or \\0ooo."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:47
msgid "``%%`` signifies a literal \"%\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:49
msgid ""
"Conversion can fail, e.g. \"102.234\" can't losslessly convert to an "
"integer, causing printf to print an error. If you are okay with losing "
"information, silence errors with ``2>/dev/null``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:51
msgid ""
"A number between the ``%`` and the format letter specifies the width. The "
"result will be left-padded with spaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:54
msgid "Backslash Escapes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:55
msgid "printf also knows a number of backslash escapes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:57
msgid "``\\\"`` double quote"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:58
msgid "``\\\\`` backslash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:59
msgid "``\\a`` alert (bell)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:60
msgid "``\\b`` backspace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:61
msgid "``\\c`` produce no further output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:62
msgid "``\\e`` escape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:63
msgid "``\\f`` form feed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:64
msgid "``\\n`` new line"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:65
msgid "``\\r`` carriage return"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:66
msgid "``\\t`` horizontal tab"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:67
msgid "``\\v`` vertical tab"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:68
msgid "``\\ooo`` octal number (ooo is 1 to 3 digits)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:69
msgid "``\\xhh`` hexadecimal number (hhh is 1 to 2 digits)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:70
msgid "``\\uhhhh`` 16-bit Unicode character (hhhh is 4 digits)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:71
msgid "``\\Uhhhhhhhh`` 32-bit Unicode character (hhhhhhhh is 8 digits)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:74
msgid "Errors and Return Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:75
msgid ""
"If the given argument doesn't work for the given format (like when you try "
"to convert a number like 3.141592 to an integer), printf prints an error, to "
"stderr. printf will then also return non-zero, but will still try to print "
"as much as it can."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:77
msgid ""
"It will also return non-zero if no argument at all was given, in which case "
"it will print nothing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:79
msgid ""
"This printf has been imported from the printf in GNU Coreutils version 6.9. "
"If you would like to use a newer version of printf, for example the one "
"shipped with your OS, try ``command printf``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:82
msgid "Example"
msgstr "範例"

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:86
msgid "printf '%s\\t%s\\n' flounder fish"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:88
msgid ""
"Will print \"flounder    fish\" (separated with a tab character), followed "
"by a newline character. This is useful for writing completions, as fish "
"expects completion scripts to output the option followed by the description, "
"separated with a tab character."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:92
msgid "printf '%s: %d' \"Number of bananas in my pocket\" 42"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:94
msgid "Will print \"Number of bananas in my pocket: 42\", `without` a newline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:97
msgid "See Also"
msgstr "另請參見"

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:99
msgid "the :doc:`echo <echo>` command, for simpler output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:102
msgid "Footnotes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/printf.rst:103
msgid ""
"In fact, while fish's ``echo`` supports ``--``, POSIX forbids it, so other "
"implementations can't be used if the input contains anything starting with "
"``-``."
msgstr ""
